<p>Like thousands of others I have been annoyed by the many ways CkEditor changes or removes code pasted into Source Area when switching back to wysiwyg.</p>  <p>In my OpenCart store I am trying to get slideshow known as CSSSlider (cssslider.com) to work in CKEditor, so that it plays in wysiwyg view and of course plays when page is published.  With the following codes in config.js I have stopped all but a few instances of CKEditor changing the cssslider embed code pasted into Source Area:</p>  <pre><code>/**  * @license Copyright (c) 2003-2015, CKSource - Frederico Knabben. All rights reserved.  * For licensing, see LICENSE.md or http://ckeditor.com/license  */  CKEDITOR.editorConfig = function( config ) {     // Define changes to default configuration here. For example:     // config.language = 'fr';     // config.uiColor = '#AADC6E'; config.extraPlugins = 'docsembedder'; config.baseHref = 'http://www.worldproaudio.com/store/'; config.allowedContent = true; CKEDITOR.dtd.$removeEmpty.span = 0; config.extraAllowedContent = 'span(*)';    $.each(CKEDITOR.dtd.$removeEmpty, function (i, value) {         CKEDITOR.dtd.$removeEmpty[i] = false;     });  }; </code></pre>  <p>The following codes are still being changed and I think if the changes could be prevented the last little bit of oddities in the way slideshow looks and feels when published will be cured:</p>  <p>input name is being changed to input class:</p>  <p>this:</p>  <pre><code>&lt;input name="cs_anchor1" id="cs_slide1_0" type="radio" class="cs_anchor slide"&gt; </code></pre>  <p>is changed to:</p>  <pre><code>&lt;input class="cs_anchor slide" id="cs_slide1_1" name="cs_anchor1" type="radio" /&gt; </code></pre>  <p>and this:</p>  <pre><code>&lt;input name="cs_anchor1" id="cs_play1" type="radio" class="cs_anchor" checked=""&gt; </code></pre>  <p>is being changed to:</p>  <pre><code>&lt;input checked="checked" class="cs_anchor" id="cs_play1" name="cs_anchor1" type="radio" /&gt; </code></pre>  <p>Any thoughts on this one?  There are so many questions posted like mine that CKEditor and StackOverflow really should post in one place a thorough response that covers 95% of the common CKEditor code changing issues.</p>  <p>Thanks</p>  <p>Rob</p>